    <div class="explanation">
        <p><strong>What are Dual-Function Prepositions?</strong></p>
        <p>Dual-function prepositions (Wechselpräpositionen) are prepositions that can take either the <strong>Dative</strong> or <strong>Accusative</strong> case, depending on whether they indicate a location (Wo? - Where?) or a direction (Wohin? - Where to?).</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Dative (Wo?)</strong> - Indicates a static location or position</li>
            <li><strong>Accusative (Wohin?)</strong> - Indicates movement or direction toward a destination</li>
            <li><strong>Dative (Woher?)</strong> - Indicates origin or source (where from?)</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

  

    <div class="note">
        <div class="note-title">&#128221; Important Notes:</div>
        <p><strong>Contracted Forms:</strong></p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>(m./n./f.)</strong> - merges with masculine, neutral and feminine definite articles "der", "das", "die"<br>
                Example: in dem → im, zu der → zur</li>
            <li><strong>(m./n.)</strong> - merges with masculine and neutral definite articles "der", "das"<br>
                Example: in dem → im, an dem → am</li>
            <li><strong>(n.)</strong> - merges with neutral definite article "das"<br>
                Example: in das → ins, auf das → aufs</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Usage:</strong> The contracted form is mostly used in normal speech. The non-contracted form sounds to Germans as if you want to describe a specific thing more detailed, similar to "the" and "this".</p>
        <p><strong>Preposition Patterns:</strong> For the questions "wo - where" and "wohin - where to" the prepositions for location and direction are mostly equal. For the question "woher - where from" the prepositions are often a little bit different.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="example">
        <div class="example-title">&#128172; Example Conversation:</div>
        <p><strong>[A]:</strong> Ich bin <span class="contracted">am</span> See. <em>(I am at the lake.)</em></p>
        <p><strong>[B]:</strong> An welchem See bist du? <em>(At which lake are you?)</em></p>
        <p><strong>[A]:</strong> Ich bin <strong>an dem</strong> See mit der Insel. <em>(I am at the lake with the island.)</em></p>
        <p style="margin-top: 15px; padding: 10px; background-color: rgba(255,255,255,0.7); border-left: 3px solid #2874a6;">
            <strong>Explanation:</strong> Notice how "am" (contracted) is used for general reference, while "an dem" (non-contracted) is used to specify a particular lake.
        </p>
    </div>

    <h2>The Nine Core Wechselpräpositionen</h2>
    <div class="explanation">
        <p>The nine main dual-function prepositions are:</p>
        <ol style="columns: 2; -webkit-columns: 2; -moz-columns: 2;">
            <li><strong>an</strong> - at, on, to</li>
            <li><strong>auf</strong> - on, upon, onto</li>
            <li><strong>hinter</strong> - behind</li>
            <li><strong>in</strong> - in, into</li>
            <li><strong>neben</strong> - next to, beside</li>
            <li><strong>über</strong> - over, above, across</li>
            <li><strong>unter</strong> - under, below, among</li>
            <li><strong>vor</strong> - in front of, before</li>
            <li><strong>zwischen</strong> - between</li>
        </ol>
    </div>

